Here's a simple implementation of a function that converts markdown to HTML using the `std::string` and `std::regex` from the `<regex>` library:

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Headers
    html += "<p>"; // Wrap the whole text in a paragraph
    std::regex headerRegex("^#+(.*)$", std::regex::icase);
    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), headerRegex), end; it != end; ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<h" + (match.str(1)[0] - '1' == '1' ? "1" : match.str(1)[0] - '2' == '1' ? "2" : "3") + ">" + match.str(1) + "</h" + (match.str(1)[0] - '1' == '1' ? "1" : match.str(1)[0] - '2' == '1' ? "2" : "3") + "></p><p>";
    }
    html.pop_back(); // Remove the extra '</p>' at the end

    // Bold and Italic
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("\\*([^*]+)\*", std::regex::icase, "$1");
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("_(.+)_", std::regex::icase, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Links
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("\\[(.+?)\\]\\(([^)]+)\\)", std::regex::icase, "<a href=\"$2\" title=\"$1\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}
```

This function converts the following markdown syntax:

* Headers: `# Heading` becomes `<h1>Heading</h1>`, `## Heading` becomes `<h2>Heading</h2>`, and `### Heading` becomes `<h3>Heading</h3>`
* Bold: `*Bold text*` remains as is (no change)
* Italic: `_Italic text_` becomes `<em>Italic text</em>`
* Links: `[Link Text](http://www.example.com)` becomes `<a href="http://www.example.com" title="Link Text">Link Text</a>`

Note that this is a basic implementation and may not cover all possible markdown syntax variations. You can extend the regular expressions to support more features as needed.

